{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496894","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496894"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:58:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:58:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1432"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1432"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.75,0.04,0.03,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1432"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47056"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1432"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1432"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31809"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8097"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5723"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6048"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42317"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47056"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 26-year old-man presents to his General Practitioner with lesions on his hand (Image) which developed around three weeks ago. At that time, he had warts on his hand which were treated with the help of a dermatologist. He has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On physical examination there are no other abnormalities detected. The patient is a wildlife ranger and is often exposed to various animals but does not recall any recent incidents of bites.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Contagious pustular dermatitis/ecthyma contagiosum (Orf) following ovine bite","Blood-filled bullae following overaggressive cryotherapy","Haematomas following excision of precancerous lesions","Bullous fixed drug eruption","Bullous pemphigoid"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Eblood-filled bullae following overaggressive cryotherapy.\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0These bullae were caused by the overaggressive application of liquid nitrogen. Cryotherapy is an appropriate first-line treatment of common warts, particularly in the immunocompetent patient. Other first-line options for treatment include debridement and salicylic acid with duct tape occlusion, or silver nitrate solution. This is an immunocompetent patient without any history of bleeding diathesis. The proposed mechanism of action is that the spray gun was applied for too long, causing tissue damage sufficient to lead to the development of large blood-filled bullae.\u00a0\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEcthyma contagiosum (Orf, or contagious pustular dermatitis)\u003C/strong\u003E is due to infection with the orf virus, a Parapox virus which infects sheep, goats, and various other animals. Transmission is via contact with infected animals. It manifests with pustular papules or nodules, unlike the bullae shown in the images.\u00a0\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EThere is \u003Cstrong\u003Eno evidence of recent excision \u003C/strong\u003Eand the appearance of an encapsulated tense lesion does not suggest haematomas.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBullous fixed drug eruption \u003C/strong\u003Eis a possible differential to consider if there is no preceding inciting event that makes it more likely. However, this form of eruption occurs within 24-48hrs post-exposure to the culprit drug. In light of no history suggesting use of any prescription or over-the-counter medication, it would seem unlikely.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBullous pemphigoid (BP)\u003C/strong\u003E is an immunobullous condition. This presents with intact blisters that may or may not be filled with blood. This is unlikely in this case as this is a very localised presentation and BP will present with generalised involvement. The young age of the patient also makes it highly unlikely, as BP tends to involve elderly patients. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Blood-filled bullae are most commonly seen in patients who have received aggressive cryotherapy as a treatment for warts."],"references":["Witchey DJ, Witchey NB, Roth-Kauffman MM, et al. Plantar Warts: Epidemiology, Pathophysiology, and Clinical Management. J Am Osteo Assoc 2018; 118:92-104."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31809"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1432"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15189"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15189"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/25ef5647-e985-4f66-9af7-1cd28e6d32e0.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/25ef5647-e985-4f66-9af7-1cd28e6d32e0.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":533}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31809"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-15T17:22:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-06-15T17:22:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id"